  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Augustus Hesse is glad that Deborah Weston is home again because &quot;everything goes the wrong way&quot; when she is not there. Augustus Hesse believes that he would have been successful [in obtaining his furlough?] if Deborah had taken care of his affairs. &quot;Now I do not know if I shall be able to see Mrs. Weston all my friends &amp; Almira &amp; little Anna---I am Sorrow I do not know hardly what to write. Afflictedness is my pastime now.&quot; Hesse describes the long red tape involved in procuring a furlough. Dr. Brown [from the hospital] does not favor Augustus Hesse and takes no interest in the matter. Hesse appealed to Governor Andrew, who wrote to the surgeon in charge of the hospital, &quot;who gave the letter I beleave [sic] to Dr. Brown,&quot; who did not like it. Peter has been drafted. Hesse wishes that Peter would join the Massachusetts Battery. Hesse does not believe the war will last long. He has heard a rumor that General Lee has tendered his resignation.</subfield>
